#include <iostream>
#include <string>

class Player {
    // Forgot 'public:' — everything is private by default!
    std::string name;
    int health;

    Player(std::string n) {  // Private constructor!
        name = n;
        health = 100;
    }
};

int main() {
    // ERROR: Can't access private constructor!
    Player hero("Hero");

    return 0;
}

phase2.explanation:
In C++, everything in a `class` is **private** by default. You need `public:` to make it accessible.

**What's happening:**
- The constructor is private
- You can't create `Player` objects outside the class
- The fields are also private

**The fix:**
```cpp
class Player {
public:  // ← Add this!
    std::string name;
    int health;

    Player(std::string n) {
        name = n;
        health = 100;
    }
};
```

**PlusPlus-chan says:**
"Unlike structs, class members are private by default. That's intentional — it encourages encapsulation. But you need `public:` to use them."

